column2: Breezy- bright sun- 10 inch waves- difficult getting reading- lake level down 3 or 4 inches from previous reading.
Cloudy- bright day- few white caps- rain threatening.
Cloudy- bright day with a light wind.  Last report for season.
Fair weather- breezy.  Foul weather delayed this reading several days.
Calm- algae appearing- and there has been windy weather recently.
Low rainfall and above normal temperatures have raised the water temperatures well above normal for this date.
Bright- clear- and the water is stirred up by earlier storm.
Bright day- partly cloudy- algae on the increase.
Cloudy but bright- calm- no boat activity.
Breezy- 6-8" waves- more than usual boat activity.
Breezy- low level of boat activity.
Breezy day- clear and bright- last report of the season.
Breezy- bright day- a few white caps on the water.
Breezy- some white caps- bright sun.
Overcast but bright- light wind- lake level falling .1 foot per week.
Lake dropping .1 ft. every 10 days- clear- bright- light breeze.
Algae- heavy rains- strong sewer smell from resorts.
Bright- choppy waves- algae on increase- strong winds delayed reading.
Bright- light breeze- strong breezes delayed reading.
Clear bright day- calm- heavy rain the previous day.
Lake highest all season- bright day- breezy.
Ice out 4/22- bright + breezy- turbulent water.
Heavy rain and wind night before- bright sun but rough lake when read.
Cloudy and breezy- 2 days of rain.
Bright- breezy day- lake level falling.
Clear and bright- light breeze- level is falling.
Bright day- light breeze- low boat activity.
Cloudy- bright- breezy- storm coming in- warm and humid.
Cloudy- breezy- algae beginning to accumulate.
Bright and breezy- occasional whitecaps- over 9 in. rain past 2 weeks.
Bright sun- strong winds- white caps.
Calm- bright- level is high but falling.
Calm- bright- weeds disappearing- last report.
Cloudy- bright- breezy- white caps-"not a good reading".
Bright- partly. cloudy- light waves- recent storms.
Overcast but bright- turbulent water from windy days.
Bright- breezy- choppy- leaky dam losing water.
Dark- cloudy- slight. chop- most algae bloom seen in 4 seasons.
Bright- calm- never seen so much algae bloom in Bear Lake.
Bright but hazy- 2.25" rain last P.M.- high winds.
Bright sun- breezy- windy past 3 days- very rough.
Light breeze- no boats- last reading.
Bright- breezy- whitecaps- water turbid- water level highest in years.
Cloudy- bright- slight wind- sample delayed due to bad weather.
Sunny- breezy- turbid water.  Lake level: very high
Algae bloom- murky water- sunny- sight breeze.
Partly cloudy- light breeze- more algae than ever.
Clear- heavy rain this week- algae level very high.
Ice off 4-22. Three days of high winds caused turbidity.
Fish starting to bite- bluegills spawning.
Two days of strong winds- clear- bright day.
Clear bright day.  The lake is recovering very well from excessive algae and carried in debris of last years excessive rains.
Bright sun- light breeze.  Lake beautiful.
Algae on increase.  Cloudy bright day.
Bright- breezy morning.  Lake is beautiful.
Bright- breezy day.  Algae growth on decline.
Bright sunny day- breezy- algae are disappearing.
Clear- bright- hazy day.  Little evidence of algae.
Sunny- 3.5" rain raised water level 7" in a few days.
Water turbid- previous high winds and rain- breezy day- little algae growth.
Clear sky- light breeze- algae colonies appearing.
Mostly cloudy- brisk breeze- some whitecaps.
Bright- clear evening.  No waves- warm and humid.
Light haze- bright clear day- algae on increase.
Bright sunny day- breezy.  Algae are on increase.
Strong wind last two days.  Algae bloom diminishing.  Light breeze today.  Partly cloudy.
Bright- breezy day.  Last report of the season.
Bright sunny evening- small waves- saw 3 bald eagles.
Light broken cloud cover- waves near white cap stage.
Bright sunny day- light breeze.  Beautiful on the lake.
Bright day- breezy- algae bloom appearing.
Overcast.  Almost calm.  My earlier readings are probably 1' short.  New disc.
Overcast- but bright.  Breezy.  Algae bloom still light.
Mostly cloudy.  Light chop on water.  Rain delayed check.  Algal growth increasing.
Recent heavy rains have increased turbidity.  Mostly cloudy- but bright morning.
Lake was too rough to go out on the 12-14th.  My boat isn't big enough.  Algae on increase.  Bright day- breezy.
Clear sky- bright sun- calm water.
The 3rd and 4th were too rough to go out.  The 5th was a mostly clear and bright day.  Some white caps- algae on decline.
Clear- bright- breezy day.  White caps on water- last report of the season.
Hot-sunny-dead calm-ideal for secchi disk reading.
Sunny- clear and light northerly breeze.
Partly cloudy.  Light WNW.  Hot + humid.
Mostly cloudy.  Light easterly wind.  1/3" of rain this A.M.
Partly cloudy- light west wind.  Lake about 10" above normal.
Mostly cloudy- SE breeze.  Lake about 4"above normal.
Mostly cloudy- light south breeze.  Lake about 6" above normal.
Mostly cloudy- light east breeze.  Lake about 10" above normal.
100% cloud cover.  East wind.  Lake about 6" above normal.
Clear and calm. Heavy rain last night.
Total cloud cover- light SE wind.
Total cloud cover. Light SE wind.
Cloudy- calm.  5.0 inches rain past week.
Rain and wind most of last 10 days.
Overcast SE wind - breezy.  Dave from DNR demonstrating.
Mostly cloudy- N wind 15 mph.  Andy Medzis being oriented.  Temp. gauge only to 70'.
Medzis brought depth finder.  Mostly cloudy.  SSW wind.  Light waves.  Temp. gauge to 80'.  Over 2 weeks in 80s-90+ degrees F.  Periodic dry spells.
Mostly sunny- SSE wind.  Waves 3-4 inches.  Temp. gauge to 80 feet.  5 days prior:  9" rain.  Lake level up approx. 1 foot.
calm- clear- slight haze in distance- no heavy rain- one week prior over .6 inches in four days- temp gauge to 80F
Mostly cloudy SE wind- 3-4 inch wave action- unseasonably warm over week ago less .10 inches rain- recent panfish die off- temp. gauge to 80F
clear- 4-5 inch waves- light choppy- no whites-- unseasonably warm and dry- trial temp. gauge to 90F- Colorometric D.O. method being used
clear- gentle 2-3 inch waves- unusual D.O. at 30-35ft as was August 2005- on 9-5-06 Secchi was 5.3ft as per Steve McComas- Blue Water Science
clear- 3-4 inch waves- Sept. cooler than average- snow flurries 11-12-13- 1 inch accumulation 10-13-06- .6 inches rain each week past two weeks
Low precipitation in area. Water clarity is impressive.  Records indicate that similar secchi reading of +12' has been achieved.  Larger snails are more visible.
Overcast- rain. 2-3 in. waves- air temp. 42F.

column1: Lake level recently high- late ice out

column2: Overcast- raining- 2-3" waves- outside air temperature 42 degrees F

column1: Lake level recently high- late ice-out

column2: Overcast - mist- 4-5 inch roller waves- increase Curly-leaf pond weed 2007-08- more abundant Chinese Mystery Snail
additonal to follow overcast misty- 4-5" waves- increase sightings of Curlyleaf pondweed from 2007 to 2008- more abundant Chinese Mystery Snails
Slight overcast and hazy- 2-3" waves- moderate breeze- no recent rain- Curlyleaf pondweed is dying off.
Slightly overcast - hazy- 2-3 inch waves- moderate breeze- no recent rain. Curly leaf pondweed dying
Slight algae bloom- gentle breeze- sunny bright skies- little rain during month- received 0.4" on 27 AUG
Sunny- gentle breeze- blooming- less rain past month- on 08/27 0.4 in. rain
NNW wind-10-12mph- 5-6" waves- very dry Spring- clear skies
Calm- overcast- very dry in May- rain in past 24hrs (0.7"-1.5")- curlyleaf pondweed present- Chinese Mystery Snails observed
Partly cloudy-very dry conditions- droughtlike- although recent rain in past 1-4 days with amounts of .20 and .15"- 5-6" waves- windy- quality looks good
Mostly sunny- calm and dry- rain one week ago- light breeze- no waves- just ripple surface- algae bloom started. purple loosestrife noticed
Ptly cloudy  NNW breeze   4" ripple/waves  fewer# of snails-  +Prpl Lstrf
Preparation- sampling- testing- clean-up 1500-1800 hrs. Dry July. 5-6" waves- Fewer Chinese Mystery Snails. Curly leaf pondweed dying off. Purple Loosestrife persists. Two guests observed procedures.

Light WEST wind at 5-6 mph. Ripple surface. Recent rains. Overcast with few breaks of partial sun. Chinese Mystery Snails present.  WEST wind at 5-6 mph ripple surface. Recent rains. Overcast w occasional sunlight breaks. Chinese Mystery Snails present and abundant.
Warm weather (upper 80's) slight breeze w clear sunshine most of day. Humid weather for three days. Rains have missed this area past few days.
Additional lake association members were present to observed and participate in the sampling and testing. Found it educational and enjoyed the activity.  Observers: Jean Medzis and Bill Evans.

column1: WEATHER: Mostly sunny with partial cloud activity. Light breeze from Southeast at 8-10 mph. 3-5" small waves. air temperature 81 F
Paired loons with one chick swimming and short dive attempts by the young loon. Several eagles and Ospreys

column2: Overcast with occasional clearing skies. Slight breeze from SE at 6-8 mph. 4-6" wave action. Past few days have mild steady temperatures- with on/off light rain and overcast skies.
Performed Secchi Disc reading to coordinate with satellite Path 26. Secchi reading 8.50 feet.
Secchi Disk only to coordinate with Satellite Path 26
Secchi  Disk reading only to coordinate with Satellite Path 26
Secchi Disk reading only to coordinate with Satellite Path 26

SE wind approximately 8-10 mph. Thin cloud cover provided bright lighting (shadows were produced). Recent heavy rains and thunderstorms resulting in some runoff from shorelines.  Time 1000-1300 for equipment cleaning and drying- rope drying.

Also had Bill Evans to observe and assist both "on-water" and "shore" procedures. Was not able to add him to the list of data collectors. Dorothy Moe stated that a few of the lake residents had observed fish dead and floating on surface of water.

Today: Mostly Sunny Temps in the low 70's heading to the upper 70's. Wind WNW @ 5-7 mph occasional gusts @9-10 mph . Light wave action @ 4-6". Starting to see algae growth suspended in water. Water and Air temps have been warm. Recent rain storms with strong winds may be contributing.

column1: Curlyleaf Pondweed is visibly brown and floating near water-surface.
Several Loon pairs with 2 chicks each. Younger loons have changed from brown downy color to more white and lighter tones. Young eagles are in flight at low-levels.   A.Medzis

column2: Time 10:30 - 14:30 Hours. Equipment maintenance and delivery to USPS.

column1: Assisted by William Evans- noticeably more algae suspension present in the water. Curlyleaf Pondweed appears to be dieing off as more plants are turning brown. Slight breeze out of the SSW- with dryer air present.

column2: Secchi Disk reading ONLY: Coordinated with Satelite program.

column1: Bill Evans accompanied and assisted with water column temperature testing- water sample collection and secchi disk measurements. Then on-shore paperwork- chemistry and chlorophyll sampling was conducted with the additional assistance of Bob and Dorothy Moe.  Equipment was then taken to shore and prepared for drying prior to being stored.
